        (30, 'Herbs/Spices', 'True or false? Saffron is the world\'s most expensive spice.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Saffron is derived from the dark stigmas of the saffron crocus, a bulbous plant that originated in the East. At least 14,000 flowers are required to produce one ounce of saffron.'),
        (30, 'Herbs/Spices', 'True or false? The spice turmeric is in the ginger family.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Turmeric is a deep yellow tropical rhizome. It has a peppery flavor and is an essential spice in Indian cooking. Hindus associate it with fertility. '),
        (30, 'History', 'True or false? The muffuletta sandwich originated in New York.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'The muffuletta was developed in New Orleans in 1906 at the Central Grocery by an Italian immigrant. '),
        (30, 'Meat', 'True or false? The white of the egg is very low in protein.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Egg whites (albumen) are almost pure protein. '),
        (30, 'Meat', 'True or false? A slice of ham with an iridescent greenish sheen is spoiled.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'The green is a sign of oxidation and does not necessarily mean that the meat is spoiled. When exposed to oxygen or light, some of the nitrate-modified iron content of the meat undergoes a chemical change that alters the ham\'s pigmentation.'),
        (30, 'Meat', 'True or false? Head cheese is made with sheep\'s milk.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Head cheese is not actually cheese, but a jellied sausage made from the head of a pig or calf. '),
        (30, 'Meat', 'True or false? New York steak is cut from the tenderloin.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'A New York cut is from the short or strip loin and is the boneless top loin muscle. '),
        (30, 'Meat', 'True or false? Pemmican is a type of fried unleavened bread.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Pemmican is a North American Aboriginal cake of dried and pounded meat, berries (such as blueberries or cranberries) and melted fat. The name comes from the Algonquin word "pime," which means "fat.'),
        (30, 'Meat', 'True or false? "Poussin" is the French term for a small, young chicken. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Meat', 'True or false? Prosciutto is a type of smoked ham.', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Prosciutto is dry-cured and aged. '),
        (30, 'Meat', 'True or false? A pullet is a young turkey.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'A pullet is a chicken that is younger than one year. '),
        (30, 'Meat', 'True or false? Mortadella and mettwurst are dry sausages. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'They are smoked sausages; however, mortadella is cooked and mettwurst is uncooked. '),
        (30, 'Meat', 'True or false? Serrano and Iberico are two great Spanish cheeses.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Both are world-famous hams. Although Serrano is more popular, Iberico is considered one of the best in the world.'),
        (30, 'Meat', 'True or false? The most humane methods of animal slaughter result in the highest quality meat. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'It has been known for centuries that stressing animals before slaughter adversely affects the quality of the meat. '),
        (30, 'dairy', 'True or false? Condensed milk is sweetened before being reduced.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Sugar is added after the water has been removed. Unopened condensed milk keeps almost indefinitely.'),
        (30, 'Misc.', 'True or false? In Japanese cuisine, the term "agemono" refers to deep frying.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Tempura (deep-fried vegetables or seafood) is the best-known dish cooked using the agemono method. '),
        (30, 'Misc.', 'True or false? Bird\'s nest soup is made from noodles that resemble a bird\'s nest.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Bird\'s nest soup is made from the nests of cave swifts in southeast Asia. The nests have been used in Chinese cooking for over 400 years. They are difficult to obtain and process, and are among the most expensive animal products consumed by humans. '),
        (30, 'Misc.', 'True or false? An egg that sinks when placed in water is fresh.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'The gases in eggs increase over time, causing them to become more buoyant as they age. '),
        (30, 'Misc.', 'True or false? Honey contains no cholesterol.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'It also contains no fat or fiber but it is high in carbohydrates. '),
        (30, 'Misc.', 'True or false? Honey is believed to be the only food that does not spoil.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Honey found in ancient Egyptian tombs has been tasted and found edible. '),
        (30, 'Nuts', 'True or false? The Brazil nut is the toughest of all nuts to crack.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'The black walnut has the hardest shell. In addition, it is covered by a thick husk that exudes a dark, staining, strong-smelling juice that can be extremely difficult to remove from clothing and hands.'),
        (30, 'Nuts', 'True or false? Peanuts are cholesterol free.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Nuts', 'True or false? The pecan is native to the US.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'The pecan is a member of the hickory family. '),
        (30, 'Oils', 'True or false? Balsamic vinegar is made from wine.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Balsamic vinegar is made from grape pressings that have never fermented into wine. '),
        (30, 'Oils', 'True or false? Balsamic vinegar is always aged in oak casks. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Chestnut, cherrywood, ash, mulberry and juniper kegs are also used, and each adds a distinctive character to the vinegar. '),
        (30, 'Oils', 'True or false? Grapeseed oil has a relatively low smoke point, which means that it burns at a lower temperature than other oils.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Grapeseed oil has a high smoke point and is, therefore, ideal for sautéeing. '),
        (30, 'Oils', 'True or false? Olive oil should be stored in the refrigerator. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'The best way to store olive oil is to cap it tightly and store it in a cool, dark place. If stored properly olive oil can last a couple of years, although after being stored for one year, the oil should be used only for cooking.'),
        (30, 'Oils', 'True or false? Omega-3 oils are found only in fish.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Although Omega-3 oils are found in the tissues of all sea creatures, particularly in high-fat fish, this highly beneficial oil is also found in flax seed and walnut oil. '),
        (30, 'Oils', 'True or false? Palm oil contains transfats.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Palm oil does not contain transfats but it does contain saturated fat. However, it is also rich in antioxidants and vitamins.'),
        (30, 'Oils', 'True or false? All vegetable oils are low in cholesterol and contain virtually no saturated fatty acids.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Palm and coconut oils contain almost equal amounts of saturated fatty acids and animal fats. '),
        (30, 'Oils', 'True or false? Corn, olive and sunflower oils contain unsaturated fatty acids.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Pasta', 'True or false? In northern Italy, the preference is for pasta made with added egg.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Egg pasta originated in Emilia. The added egg strengthens the dough.'),
        (30, 'Pasta', 'True or false? The semolina that is used to make pasta is made from  finely ground durum wheat. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Semolina is a food obtained by grinding cereal. Polenta is made from corn semolina. Pasta is made from hard durum wheat semolina. '),
        (30, 'Pasta', 'True or false? Japanese soba noodles are made from rice.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Soba noodles are made from buckwheat and are traditionally used in soups. '),
        (30, 'Pasta', 'True or false? Spaghetti is thicker than spaghettini.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Processed Foods', 'True or false? Peanut butter was originally created as a thickening agent.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Peanut butter was invented in 1890 by Dr. John Kellogg (who also invented cornflakes) as a healthy protein substitute for meat.'),
        (30, 'processed foods', 'True or false? Tabasco sauce was named after Miguel Tabasco, who first blended it in the early 1900s in Mexico.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Tabasco sauce is named for the state of Tabasco in southern Mexico. '),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? Plums are associated with the term à la Montmorency.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Dishes prepared à la Montmorency include cherries. '),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? Aïoli is a tomato-based preparation.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Aïoli is a garlic mayonnaise from Provence, in southern France. '),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? Blinis are made from corn. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Blinis are usually made from buckwheat. In Russia, blinis are traditionally served warm with caviar and salmon.'),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? A caroline is a sweet, cream-filled dessert.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'A caroline is a savory éclair made of choux pastry filled with cold liver mousse or hot purée of salmon. '),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? Carpaccio is beef poached in red wine.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Carpaccio is thin slices of raw beef, often served with lemon juice, mayonnaise, capers and onions. '),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? Chicken à la king is made with onions, peas and carrots. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'This dish is usually made with mushrooms, green peppers, pimentos, cream and, occasionally, sherry. '),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? Cooked potatoes that have been puréed, combined with butter and egg yolks then baked are called Princess potatoes.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'The name for this dish is Duchess potatoes. '),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? Escabèche is made with fish. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'The fish is sautéed or fried, then marinated and refrigerated. Escabèche is usually served cold, as an appetizer.'),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? A flamiche is a leek and cheese tart.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Flamiche, which comes from northern France and Flanders, can also contain onions. Flamiche is a Flemish word for "cake.'),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? A fricassee is a deep-fried dish of chicken or other meat. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'A fricassee is a dish of meat that is sautéed in butter then stewed with vegetables and sometimes wine. '),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? The Spanish word for beans is "frijoles."', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? Futomaki is a kind of saki.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Futomaki is a thick sushi roll of veggies, fish and tofu wrapped in rice and seaweed. '),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? Flounder is used in gefilte fish.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Carp is used in this Jewish dish. The fish is ground and mixed with eggs, matzo meal and seasonings, formed into patties or balls, and cooked in stock.'),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? Goulash is a dish noted for its use of garlic. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'This Hungarian dish is especially noted for its use of paprika. '),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? Calves\' stomaches are used as the casing for the Scottish specialty haggis.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Haggis is usually made with the lining of a sheep\'s stomach, which is filled with the animal\'s organs, oatmeal, onions and seasonings, then simmered in water for several hours. '),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? Corn flour is the principal ingredient of the Jewish dish latkes.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Latkes are made from grated potato mixed with egg, onion and seasonings, and fried in the form of a pancake. '),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? Osso buco is an Italian dish made with veal.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Osso buco consists of a veal shank, cut across the bone into one-inch slices that are browned and braised in white wine and aromatics. Its name literally means "bone with a hole.'),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? Piccata is an Italian dish of spiced ham.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Piccata is veal scallops, fried in butter and glazed with Marsala wine and lemon juice. '),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? The Basque specialty known as pipérade usually contains rabbit.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Other than onions, green peppers and tomatoes, typical ingredients are egg, garlic or ham. '),
        (30, 'Recipes', 'True or false? Welsh rarebit is made with beef.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Welsh rarebit (or rabbit) is a slice of toast covered with Cheddar cheese melted in beer. It contains neither beef nor rabbit.'),
        (30, 'Sauce', 'True or false? Albert sauce is made with chutney.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Albert sauce is a rich horseradish sauce of butter, flour and cream. It was dedicated to Prince Albert, the husband and consort of Queen Victoria.'),
        (30, 'Sauce', 'True or false? The term "au jus" refers to a meat served with tomato sauce.', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Au jus refers to meat served with its natural, unthickened pan juices. '),
        (30, 'Sauce', 'True or false? Beurre blanc is a sauce made with butter and flour.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Beurre blanc is made by whisking butter into a reduction of white wine, white wine vinegar, shallots and, often, fresh herbs. '),
        (30, 'Sauce', 'True or false? Chasseur sauce is served with meat dishes.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Chasseur sauce is a highly seasoned brown sauce usually consisting of mushrooms, shallots and wine. '),
        (30, 'Sauce', 'True or false? Coulis is a kind of sorbet.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Coulis is a thick sauce of puréed vegetables or fruit. It is sometimes uncooked and served chilled.'),
        (30, 'Sauce', 'True or false? Demi-glace is a low-fat ice cream.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Demi-glace is a rich brown stock in French cuisine that is used by itself or as a base for other sauces. '),
        (30, 'Sauce', 'True or false? Espagnole sauce is a kind of white sauce.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Espagnole sauce is made with a brown stock. '),
        (30, 'Sauce', 'True or false? Orgeat syrup is made from lemons.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Orgeat syrup is syrup made from sugar and almond milk and flavored with orange-flower water. '),
        (30, 'Sauce', 'True or false? A roux is made with veal stock and cream.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'A roux is a mixture of flour and butter or another fat and is cooked slowly over low heat. Rouxs are used to thicken soups and sauces.'),
        (30, 'Sauce', 'True or false? Velouté sauce is made with vegetable stock.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Velouté is made with chicken, veal, or fish stock, and thickened with butter and flour. '),
        (30, 'Science', 'True or false? Alcohol is the only food that is unaffected by the body\'s digestive system.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Alcohol passes through the stomach and intestines and into the bloodstream unchanged. '),
        (30, 'Science', 'True or false? All traces of alcohol disappear from food after at least three hours of cooking.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'After flaming a dish with brandy or liqueur, about 75 per cent of the alcohol remains. Alcohol also remains in varying percentages in baked dishes.'),
        (30, 'Science', 'True or false? Obese children are more likely to have food allergies.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Obese children are 26 per cent more likely to have food allergies than children of average weight. '),
        (30, 'Science', 'True or false? Clarified or drawn butter has a higher burning or smoking point than unclarified butter. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'This is because the milk solids and most of the water have been removed. '),
        (30, 'Science', 'True or false? Quick freezing of food is a key to maintaining its quality.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'The faster food is frozen, the smaller the ice crystals that form in and around its cells. Slow freezing causes the formation of large ice crystals that can damage proteins.'),
        (30, 'Science', 'True or false? Freezing kills bacteria in foods.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Freezing stops the growth of bacteria, but only cooking kills them. '),
        (30, 'Science', 'True or false? Salmonella bacteria emit a strong odor.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Salmonella bacteria are odorless and tasteless. '),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? Bombay duck is actually chicken.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'But it is not duck, either. It is actually a lizardfish, abundant in the waters off Mumbai, India, and is considered a delicacy. R543 When dried and salted it has a very unpleasant odor. The origin of the name "Bombay duck" is unknown.'),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? Char is a fresh water fish.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'The char is related to the salmon and is native to Arctic, sub-Arctic and alpine lakes and coastal waters. '),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? Cherrystone clams come from the east coast of the USA.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'These fairly large clams measure about 2. 5 inches in diameter.'),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? When cooking clams, one should not eat the ones that do not open.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'When a healthy clam is cooked, the muscle that keeps the two halves of the shell closed relaxes, and the shell opens. If the shell does not open, the clam was dead before cooking and should not be eaten.'),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? The United States has more varieties of crab than any other country.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? Dungeness crab is caught on the west coast of North America.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Dungeness crab is found from Alaska to Mexico. '),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? It is always preferable for a lobster to be alive at the time it is cooked or at least to be killed immediately before it is cooked .', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Pathogenic microorganisms are more numerous in lobsters than in fish. These disease-causing agents multiply rapidly after the lobster dies so the interval between death and cooking is crucial.'),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? "Nori" means "sea urchin" in Japanese.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Nori is seaweed that is usually dried in thin paper sheets and used for wrapping sushi and rice balls. '),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? Oyster crabs are so called because their shells resemble those of oysters. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'The name comes from the fact that these small crabs live inside the gills of oysters; they use the oyster for protection and live on the food that the oyster obtains for itself. '),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? Periwinkle is a type of candy.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'A periwinkle is a kind of conical mollusk, about one inch in diameter. '),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? Saltwater fish have more sodium in their flesh than freshwater fish.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', NULL),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? Scallops are mollusks. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Scallops are classified into two broad groups: bay scallops and sea scallops. In 1988 the state of New York made the Atlantic bay scallop its state shell.'),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? Snapper is both a saltwater and freshwater fish. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Snapper is a saltwater fish. Snappers (both red and yellowtail) are popular for their sweet, firm flesh. They are especially good grilled. '),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? Soft-shell crab are a separate species of crab.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Crabs must shed their shells periodically in order to grow. Soft-shell crabs are simply crabs whose new soft exterior has not ossified.'),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? Sprats are similar to herrings.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Sprats, sometimes called Bristling sardines, are small fish commonly found in the Baltic, the English Channel, the North Sea and the Atlantic. '),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? The flesh of fish is more tender than the flesh of mammals.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'The connective tissue in fish makes up about 3 per cent of its weight as opposed to 15 per cent for mammals. '),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? The meat of the female tortoise or turtle is more tender than that of the male.', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Seafood', 'True or false? Yellowtail is a kind of wild duck.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'A yellowtail is a gamefish. '),
        (30, 'Service', 'True or false? In restaurants, when possible, beverages should be served from the left.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Beverages should be served from the right (with the right hand). '),
        (30, 'Service', 'True or false? When clearing a table the server should proceed in a clockwise direction.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Counterclockwise. '),
        (30, 'Service', 'True or false? A fee charged by some restaurants to open and serve a bottle of wine brought by a patron is referred to as ullage.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'It is called a corkage fee. '),
        (30, 'Service', 'True or false? An arrangement of china, silverware, a napkin and glassware is called a cover.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'The contents of the cover can vary, depending on the kind of service. '),
        (30, 'Service', 'True or false? When possible, food should be served from the left.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Left side (with the left hand). '),
        (30, 'Service', 'True or false? Etiquette requires diners to fold their dinner napkin in half and place it on their lap.', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Service', 'True or false? In French service, a réchaud is used to hold unwanted food and used utensils.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'A réchaud is a small stove used to keep food and plates warm before service. '),
        (30, 'Service', 'True or false? Two servers are required in French service.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Other staff can include the captain, who seats the patrons, and the sommelier, who serves the wine. '),
        (30, 'Service', 'True or false? The proper way to eat soup is to fill the soup spoon as you move it towards yourself.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'To eat soup properly, you should fill the spoon as you move it toward the far rim of the bowl, away from yourself. '),
        (30, 'Service', 'True or false? A station is where the maitre d\' controls the seating of the dining room.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'The station is a section of the dining room assigned as a work area to a server. '),
        (30, 'Service', 'True or false? If a server seats three people at a table set for four, he or she should remove the unnecessary fourth table setting.', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Soup', 'True or false? Cockles are chestnuts.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Cockles are bivalve mollusks. '),
        (30, 'Soup', 'True or false? Gazpacho soup is made with beef.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Gazpacho is a cold meatless soup that is usually made from puréed tomatoes and other vegetables, garlic and olive oil. It comes from the Andalusian region of Spain.'),
        (30, 'Soup', 'True or false? Manhattan clam chowder is made with cream.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Manhattan clam chowder is made with tomatoes; New England clam chowder is made with cream. '),
        (30, 'Soup', 'True or false? "Minestra" is the Italian word for "mixed vegetables."  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Minestra means "soup" in Italian. "Minestrone" means a "thick and hearty soup," and "minestrina" means "broth.'),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? Absinthe is a liqueur.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Absinthe is an anise-flavored spirit made from herbs, including the leaves and flowers of wormwood. Because it does not contain added sugar, it is classified as a liquor.'),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? Advocaat is a bitter Swedish liqueur.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Advocaat is a liqueur made with brandy, egg yolks and sugar. The best-known brands (for example, Bols) come from the Netherlands.'),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? The oldest French brandy is Cognac.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'The oldest French brandy is Armagnac, the first-known distillation of which dates back to 1411. '),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? Benedictine is a whiskey-flavored liqueur.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Benedictine is a digestive made in Normandy, France, of a still-secret formula of 27 different plants and spices. '),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? A boilermaker is a shot of whiskey followed by a chaser of tomato juice.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'The whiskey is followed by a beer. '),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? Casque, Karpi and Palo and are types of smoked fish.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'They are all types of liqueurs. Casque is a honey and brandy-based liqueur from England, Karpi is a cranberry-based liqueur from Finland, and Palo is a thyme-based liqueur from Spain.'),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? Green chartreuse is colored with chlorophyll.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Only three Carthusian monks in a monastery at Voiron, near Grenoble, know the identity of the 130 plants that are blended and distilled to make chartreuse. '),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? Japan has a number of critically acclaimed whiskey producers.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'The Japanese whiskey industry dates from the 1920s. Examples of brands are Suntory, Yamazaki and Nikka.'),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? The Greek brandy Metaxa is blended with wine.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Muscat wine from the Greek islands of Samos and Lemnos is used. Metaxa was first made in 1888.'),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? Moutai is a Chinese liquor distilled from fermented sorghum and wheat.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Moutai (sometimes spelled Maotai) is arguably China\'s most famous liquor. Some versions contain up to 53 per cent alcohol by volume.'),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? The second bestselling spirit in the US is whiskey.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'It is rum. '),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? The British Royal Navy maintains a centuries-old custom of pouring a daily tot of rum for all personnel aboard its ships.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'The Royal Navy ended this custom on July 31, 1970. The anniversary is known as Black Tot Day.'),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? All rums emerge from the still as clear, colorless liquids.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Barrel aging and the addition of caramel impart the final color. '),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? Most dark rums are produced from pot stills.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Pot stills (also used to produce Cognac and Scotch whiskies) result in richer and more flavorful rums. Light rums are produced in columns or continuous stills.'),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? Sambuca is a coffee-flavored liqueur.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Sambuca is a clear anise-flavored semi-sweet Italian liqueur. When served with a couple of coffee beans in it, it is said to be "con la mosca" ("with the fly").'),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? The phrase "straight up" refers to an alcoholic drink served in a tall glass.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'A drink served straight up is served without ice. '),
        (30, 'Spirits', 'True or false? Tequila is made only from the blue agave plant.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'There are 136 species of agave in Mexico, of which the blue agave is the only one allowed to be used in tequila production. '),
        (30, 'Statistics', 'True or false? The least popular day to eat out in the US is Sunday.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'It is Monday. '),
        (30, 'Techniques', 'True or false? The word "barbecue" is derived from a French term.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'It is believed that it derives from the Arawakan word "barbacoa," which refers to a method of drying and cooking meat on a frame of wooden sticks erected over a fire. '),
        (30, 'Techniques', 'True or false? Wrapping meat with strips of fat (bacon or fatback) is referred to as larding.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'That practise is barding. Larding involves inserting fat into meat using a larding needle.'),
        (30, 'Techniques', 'True or false? The key difference between roasting and braising is the use of water. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Braising uses a small amount of water, in effect cooking with moist heat. '),
        (30, 'Techniques', 'True or false? Broiling and grilling are two methods of cooking that  both require direct heat. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Two examples of direct heat in cooking are the use of heating elements over food, as in a domestic broiler, or hot coals under the food, as in a barbecue. '),
        (30, 'Techniques', 'True or false? Coddling is a method of pickling eggs.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Coddling is a method of gently steaming or cooking food in warm water; it is a common method of preparing eggs. '),
        (30, 'Trivia', 'True or false? Paul Bocuse is the author of the cookbook titled La Technique.', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Jacques Pépin wrote La Technique. However, Paul Bocuse has also written many books about food and cooking, among them Fast Food My Way and The Apprentice: My Life in the Kitchen.'),
        (30, 'Trivia', 'True or false? Vodka is the number one selling spirit in the United States.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Utensils', 'True or false? A bain-marie is a hot-water bath used for cooking or holding food.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Also known as a double boiler, a bain-marie allows food such as custards or chocolate to be cooked or kept warm without boiling or scorching. '),
        (30, 'Utensils', 'True or false? A China cap, or chinois, refers to a lid used to cover a wok while steaming vegetables.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'A China cap is a fine-meshed cone-shaped strainer for passing sauces. '),
        (30, 'Utensils', 'True or false? Rock, saucer and sour are kinds of candy.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'They are all glassware of varying sizes used for specific kinds of beverages. '),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? Both the root and the leaves of the beet plant are edible. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Beetroots range in color from white to deep red; the leaves of the beet plant are green and highly nutritious. '),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? The best Belgian endive is green.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Endive should be white. Exposure to light causes it to turn green and to lose its delicate flavor.'),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? Broccoli belongs to the cabbage family.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'The word "broccoli" is derived from the Italian word "broccolo," which means"cabbage sprout. '),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? One should never trim the tops off bunches of carrots.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'The greens will take moisture and nutrients from the carrot if they are not removed. '),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? Eating large quantities of carrots can cause one\'s skin to turn yellow.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'This temporary condition, known as carotenosis, is caused by the non-toxic carotenoid pigments found in carrots. '),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? An individual piece of celery is referred to as a stalk. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Individual pieces of celery are referred to as ribs; many ribs make up a stalk. '),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? The name "chicken of the woods" refers to mushrooms.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Also known as "sulfur shelf," this mushroom grows in a variety of trees and often replaces chicken in cooking because of its pleasant taste and meaty texture. '),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? Corn is native to Central Africa.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Corn is native to Central America. '),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? Cucumbers are waxed primarily to prevent bruising.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Waxing helps prevent moisture loss. '),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? The garbanzo bean is also known as the chickpea.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Chickpeas are used extensively in Indian, Mediterranean and Middle Eastern dishes. '),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? The pink pickled-ginger condiment for sushi is called "cha."  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'It is called "gari. Cha" is the Japanese word for "tea.'),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? The best and most expensive maple syrup is dark.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Maple syrup should be light and clear. When it is collected from the tree, maple sap is orange; after being processed into syrup, it is golden.'),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? Wood ear, matsutake and cloud ear are varieties of mushrooms. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? As a rule, smaller peppers tend to be hotter than larger peppers.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? The potato is native to Ireland.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Potatoes are native to South America, where they were grown by the Incas. Pizarro discovered them and introduced them to Europe in 1534.'),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? Most of the heat of a radish is contained in its skin.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? Another name for green onion is scallion.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? Shitake is a type of Japanese beer. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Shitake (or Shiitake) is a meaty, flavorful mushroom. '),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? Soy milk has a higher protein content than cow\'s milk.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Soy milk is also cholesterol free, and low in fat and sodium. '),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? China produces most of the world\'s soybean crop.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'The USA is the world\'s largest producer of soybeans. '),
        (30, 'Vegetables', 'True or false? Yams and sweet potatoes are different names for the same vegetable.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Though similar in appearance and flavor, they are different. True yams are a tropical tuber with white to yellow flesh. Sweet potatoes are potatoes; they range from brown-skinned with pinkish flesh, to coppery with orange flesh. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? The longer grapes hang on the vine, the less acidic they become.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? The Alsace wine region of France borders Spain. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Alsace borders Germany. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Amarone wine is made from dried grapes.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'The fermentation of dried grapes concentrates the flavors. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? It is illegal for winemakers to add sugar to grape juice in Australia.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'It is also unnecessary because the warm climate allows grapes to ripen quickly and, therefore, to attain sweetness. In Europe, however, adding grape juice to wine is permitted.'),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Australia has only one natural grape vine.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Australia has no natural grapevine. The first grape variety was imported there in 1788.'),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? The largest fine wine producing region of Australia is the Barossa Valley.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'The Barossa Valley is situated northeast of Adelaide in southern Australia. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? "Bodega" is a Spanish word for a small café.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Bodega means a "winery" or "wine cellar" in Spanish. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Claret is synonymous with red Bordeaux wine.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Wine can only be white or red.', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Rosé or pink wines are considered red. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? A deep purple color is an indication that a wine is mature. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Deep purple is more indicative of a very young wine. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? In French, the word "cuvée" means harvest.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Cuvée refers to the blend of different grapes that are used to make a specific wine. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? "Dolce" means "soft" in Italian.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Dolce means "sweet. It is commonly used in reference to wine.'),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? "Domaine" and "château" are interchangeable terms.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'They both mean "a wine-producing property or estate" in French. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Eiswein is produced from frozen grapes. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Eiswein is a very sweet German wine made from frozen grapes. When grapes freeze on the vine, the sugars do not freeze, but the water does. This creates a highly concentrated grape must and results in a concentrated, very sweet wine. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? When a wine is referred to as "fat" it means that it contains a lot of tannin. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'A fat wine has a high glycerine content. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? The word "fino" refers to a light-bodied dry sherry.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Liebfraumilch wines can be either dry or sweet. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Completely dry Liebfraumilch wines are not allowed. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Madeira can be dry or sweet.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Madeira, which comes from the Portuguese island of the same name, is always sweet. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? The famous Marlborough wine region of New Zealand is situated on the North Island.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Marlborough is found on the South Island and is well known for its Sauvignon Blanc. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Marsala is a type of Sicilian dessert. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Marsala is a fortified wine from Sicily that comes in various styles, from dry ("secco") to sweet ("dolce"). Marsala can also be flavored with almonds, chocolate, coffee, tangerine or egg yolk.'),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Orvieto wine comes from Sicily.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Orvieto wine comes from Umbria, in central Italy. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? The French word "pétillant" refers to wines that are slightly pink. ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Pétillant means "slightly sparkling. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Phylloxera is an ancient grape variety from Croatia.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Phylloxera is a plant louse that is deadly to wine vines. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Prosecco is a sparkling wine.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Prosecco is a fruity wine from the Tre Venezie region of northeastern Italy. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Rousanne is a white grape from the Rhône region.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Rousanne is often blended with the Marsanne grape. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Salty foods tend to make red wine taste more tannic.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Salt makes red wine tend to taste less tannic. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? In France, Sauterne wines can be dry or sweet.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Sauternes are always sweet. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Genuine sherry comes from Portugal.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Sherry is a world-famous Spanish fortified wine with an alcohol content between 15. 5 per cent and 22 per cent.'),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Soave is a red wine.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'Soave is a light wine from the Tre Venezie region of northern Italy. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? In Germany, "Tafelwein" means "table wine."', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'Tafelwein is also known as ordinary wine. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? White wines contain about the same amount of tannins as red wine.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', NULL),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Valpolicella is a red wine.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'This fruity wine is made in the Tre Venezie region of northeastern Italy. '),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? Valpolicella and Bardolino wines come from the Veneto region of Italy.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? The vintage year on a wine label refers to the year the wine was bottled.   ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'B', 'The vintage refers to the year the grapes were harvested. The exception is Eiswein from Germany—the grapes for this wine are picked in January but the label shows the previous year as the vintage.'),
        (30, 'Wine', 'True or false? The great white burgundies are aged in oak casks.  ', 'True', 'False', NULL, NULL, 'A', 'The Chardonnay grape marries well with the taste of oak. '),
        (40, 'Additives', 'Kwok disease results from overuse of', 'Artificial Coloring', 'Monosodium Glutamate', 'Sulfites', NULL, 'B', 'The symptoms of Kwok\'s disease are burning pains in the chest, dizziness and numbness. '),
        (40, 'Baking', 'Johnnycakes, ashcakes and battercakes are made with which of the following?', 'Buckwheat', 'Cornmeal', 'Whole Wheat', NULL, 'B', 'These are all regional names for cornmeal flatbread. The name "ashcake" comes from the cake being cooked over the ashes of a campfire.'),
        (40, 'Baking', 'A fleuron is a type of', 'Baby Carrot', 'Chocolate', 'Pastry', NULL, 'C', 'A fleuron is a baked crescent-shaped pastry that is used as a garnish for seafood dishes in sauces. '),
        (40, 'Baking', 'In Italy, a pizza with onions, black olives and anchovies is known as', 'Ligurian', 'Margherita', 'Marinara', NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (40, 'Baking', 'What is a panettone?', 'Bread', 'Cheese', 'Sauce', NULL, 'A', 'A panettone is an Italian sweet yeast bread. It is a specialty of the city of Milan and is particularly popular at Christmas time.'),
        (40, 'Baking', 'Japanese bread crumbs used for coating fried foods are called', 'Gari', 'Kashi', 'Panko', NULL, 'C', 'Panko crumbs are coarser than the bread crumbs usually used in the US and produce a crunchier crust. '),
        (40, 'Beer', 'Which of the following is NOT a Dutch beer?', 'Amstel', 'Becks', 'Heineken', NULL, 'B', 'First brewed in Bremen, Germany, in 1873, Becks is the number one German export beer by volume and is sold in over 100 countries. '),
        (40, 'Beer', 'Bitter accounts for what percentage of draft beer sales in English pubs?', '45 Per Cent', '65 Per Cent', '80 Per Cent', NULL, 'C', 'Traditionally, bitter is unpasteurized and cask-conditioned in the pub cellar. It is highly hopped, dry and lightly carbonated.'),
        (40, 'Beverages', 'A "fifth" refers to which size of bottle?', '250 mL', '500 mL', '750 mL', NULL, 'C', 'A fifth of a gallon is about 750 mL. '),
        (40, 'beverages', 'Koumiss (or kumis) is a', 'Beverage', 'Bread', 'Cheese', NULL, 'A', 'Koumiss is a fermented dairy product traditionally made from mare\'s milk. It is important in the culture of the peoples of the Central Asian steppes.'),
        (40, 'Beverages', 'In the beverage industry, what does "ullage" refer to?', 'Airspace In The Bottle', 'Capacity Of The Glass', 'Shelf Life', NULL, 'A', 'Ullage can also refer to the empty space in a barrel or cask. '),
        (40, 'Cocktails', 'Caipirinha is the national cocktail of which country?', 'Brazil', 'Puerto Rico', 'South Africa', NULL, 'A', 'Caipirinha consists of lime, sugar and cachaça, which is made from fermented sugar cane and is the most popular distilled beverage in Brazil. '),
        (40, 'Cocktails', 'A Cosmopolitan cocktail is made with vodka, triple sec, lime juice and what other fruit juice?', 'Cranberry', 'Orange', 'Pineapple', NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (40, 'Cocktails', 'The cocktail known as French 75 is made with champagne, lemon juice, sugar and', 'Cognac', 'Crème De Cassis', 'Orange Liqueur', NULL, 'A', 'French 75 is named after a World War I artillery piece. '),
        (40, 'Cocktails', 'The cocktail Gin & It is made with gin and', 'Ginger Beer', 'Orange Liqueur', 'Sweet Vermouth', NULL, 'C', 'The Gin & It was very popular during the 1940s. Later the sweet red vermouth was replaced by dry white vermouth. Today it is referred to as a Sweet Martini. '),
        (40, 'Cocktails', 'A Mai Tai cocktail is made with lime or orange juice, curaçao, orgeat syrup and', 'Gin', 'Rum', 'Vodka', NULL, 'B', 'Either dark or light rum goes into a Mai Tai. "Maita\'i" is the Tahitian word for "good.'),
        (40, 'Cocktails', 'In what year did Victor Bergeron, known as Trader Vic, invent the Mai Tai cocktail?', '1944', '1958', '1972', NULL, 'A', 'The modern recipe is 1 oz. each of golden rum, dark rum and Triple Sec, and 1/2 oz. each of lime juice and orgeat syrup. '),
        (40, 'Cocktails', 'What is the proper garnish for a Manhattan?', 'Cherry', 'Lemon Twist', 'Olive', NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (40, 'Cocktails', 'A Mimosa is a cocktail made with orange juice and', 'Brandy', 'Champagne', 'Vermouth', NULL, 'B', NULL),
        (40, 'Cocktails', 'What whiskey is used to make a Mint Julep?', 'Bourbon', 'Rye', 'Scotch', NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (40, 'Cocktails', 'Mojito and Caipirinha are popular cocktails that contain sugar and which combination of juice and spirit?', 'Lemon And Gin', 'Lime And Rum', 'Orange And Vodka', NULL, 'B', 'Mojito is Cuban and Caipirinha is Brazilian. '),
        (40, 'Cocktails', 'A Rickey is a drink made with gin or whiskey, soda water and which juice?', 'Lime', 'Orange', 'Pineapple', NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (40, 'Cocktails', 'A Sidecar is a cocktail made with lemon juice, orange liqueur and', 'Bourbon', 'Brandy', 'Scotch', NULL, 'B', 'Cognac is also used. The Sidecar is believed to have been invented around the end of World War I in either Paris or London.'),
        (40, 'Cocktails', 'A Stinger is a cocktail of brandy or Cognac and which of the following?', 'Crème De Menthe', 'Dry Vermouth', 'Grenadine', NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (40, 'Cocktails', 'A White Lady is a cocktail made with an orange-based liqueur, lemon juice and', 'Gin', 'Vodka', 'White Wine', NULL, 'A', 'Also called a Delilah, a White Lady can also include egg whites, sugar and cream. '),
        (40, 'Coffee/Tea', 'When coffee beans are still on the tree, what fruit do they resemble?', 'Apricot', 'Cherry', 'Raspberry', NULL, 'B', NULL),
        (40, 'Coffee/Tea', 'Which of the following is NOT a black tea?', 'Assam', 'Gunpowder', 'Keemun', NULL, 'B', 'It is a green tea. '),
        (40, 'Coffee/Tea', 'In what year did Indian tea became available in Britain?', '1772', '1839', '1886', NULL, 'B', 'Indian tea was inexpensive and quickly became the national drink. '),
        (40, 'Coffee/Tea', 'Which of the following teas has a tarry, smoky flavor?', 'Keemun', 'Lapsang Souchong', 'Yunnan', NULL, 'B', NULL),
        (40, 'Coffee/Tea', 'Compared with a latte macchiato, a caffè macchiato has', 'More Milk Than Coffee', 'Less Milk Than Coffee', 'The Same Amount Of Milk And Coffee', NULL, 'B', 'A caffè macchiato is a single or double espresso topped with one or two spoonfuls of frothed milk whereas a latte macchiato is the reverse: a cup of steamed milk with a single or double espresso added. '),
        (40, 'Coffee/Tea', 'Mazagran is', 'A French Name For Cold Coffee And Seltzer', 'A Spanish Utensil For Sifting Flour', 'A Three-Liter Measure Of Wine In Italy', NULL, 'A', 'It is named for the town of Mazagran, in Algeria. '),
        (40, 'Condiments', 'Which of the following is America\'s leading food additive?', 'Monosodium Glutamate', 'Salt', 'Sugar', NULL, 'C', 'Salt is second. '),
        (40, 'Condiments', 'Wasabi is similar to which of the following?', 'Collards', 'Horseradish', 'Kohlrabi', NULL, 'B', 'This pungent Japanese condiment is made from the root of a perennial herb in the same family as mustard and broccoli. '),
        (40, 'Confectionary', 'What does the phrase "hard-crack" refer to?', 'A Degree Of Doneness In Boiled Eggs', 'A Kind Of Candy Syrup', 'A Type Of Nut Shell', NULL, 'B', 'The range of candy syrups made from sugar and water is from small-thread (least cooked) to caramel (most cooked). '),
        (40, 'Confectionary', 'Marzipan is made with sugar, egg whites and what other main ingredient?', 'Almonds', 'Hazelnuts', 'Peanuts', NULL, 'A', 'Marzipan is a popular icing for Christmas and wedding cakes. It is said to have been invented by the Ursuline order of nuns in France in the 1800s.'),
        (40, 'Confectionary', 'Which of the following is NOT a flavoring in Mexican chocolate?', 'Almond', 'Nutmeg', 'Vanilla', NULL, 'B', NULL),
        (40, 'Confectionary', 'In what country was milk chocolate invented?', 'Belgium', 'France', 'Switzerland', NULL, 'C', NULL),
        (40, 'Confectionary', 'A concoction of sugar or honey, roasted nuts and candied fruit is called', 'Manzanilla', 'Nougat', 'Ratafia', NULL, 'B', 'This sweetmeat was first made in Marseille in the 16th century and is still a specialty of southeastern France. '),
        (40, 'Confectionary', 'Ratafia does NOT refer to which of the following?', 'A Biscuit', 'A Hard Candy', 'A Liqueur', NULL, 'B', 'The ratafia biscuit and liqueur are flavored with peach or cherry kernels, bitter almonds or other fruits. '),
        (40, 'Dairy', 'Black Diamond and Cherry Hill are two examples of high quality cheddars from which country?', 'Canada', 'Great Britain', 'Usa', NULL, 'A', NULL),
        (40, 'Dairy', 'What does the term "cheddaring" refer to?', 'Aging Cheese In Wood', 'Coloring Cheese', 'Stacking, Cutting And Turning Curds', NULL, 'C', NULL),
        (40, 'Dairy', 'What country is Esrom cheese from?', 'Denmark', 'Holland', 'Norway', NULL, 'A', 'Named for its town of origin, this semi-soft cheese has a slightly pungent flavor. '),
        (40, 'Dairy', 'Feta cheese is made by pressing curds into a mould then slicing the resulting mass into slabs, which are soaked in brine. Which of these stages gives feta its name?', 'Pressing', 'Slicing', 'Soaking In Brine', NULL, 'B', 'The name is derived from the modern Greek "tyri pheta," which means "cheese slice. '),
        (40, 'Dairy', 'Gorgonzola is a kind of', 'Cheese', 'Cream-Filled Pastry', 'Pizza', NULL, 'A', 'Named for a town outside Milan where it was originally made, Gorgonzola has an ivory-colored interior and is streaked with bluish-green veins. '),
        (40, 'Dairy', 'Idiazabal is a Spanish', 'Cheese', 'Fortified Wine', 'Sausage', NULL, 'A', 'This unpasteurized sheep\'s milk cheese from the Basque and Navarre regions of Spain has a slightly smoky and nutty flavor when young. The longer-aged version is great for grating.'),
        (40, 'Dairy', 'What country does Jarlsberg cheese come from?', 'Denmark', 'Norway', 'Sweden', NULL, 'B', 'Jarlsberg is a mild Swiss-style cheese. '),
